Date: 0/0/1961
Source: Friends in Chains
Author: HENDERSON
Vol / Page: 109
Edition:
Quote: Besides all the other gear, most teamsters [c1900] carried `slippers,' which were tacked on in the event of lost shoes while on the road.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1981
Source: Both Sides of the River
Author: ANDERSON
Vol / Page: 162
Edition:
Quote: I was told that Duke had lost a shoe and ... [Bill] was tacking a slipper on him. `Tacking a slipper' on a horse means nailing on a horse-shoe that has already been used. It is tacked cold to a horse's foot. This is a temporary job to make do until the horse is ready to be shod properly.
Notes:
